description.heading: BV. Compound 81. Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-cyano-5-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate Trifluoroacetate Salt
4-(Methylthio)-2-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-carbonitrile
description.p: A mixture of 4-(methylthio)-2-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-carboxamide (500 mg, 2.9 mmol) and POCl3 (10 mL) was refluxed for 10 min. After the reaction excess solvent was removed by rotary evaporator and the residue poured onto ice-cold water. This mixture was extracted with CH2Cl2 (3×50 mL). The combined organic layers were dried over anhydrous Na2SO4, filtered and evaporated to give 4-(methylthio)-2-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-carbonitrile (400 mg, 89%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 2.8 (s, 3H); 4.96 (s, 2H).
description.heading: Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-cyano-5-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate Trifluoroacetate Salt
description.p: A mixture of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (300 mg, 0.4 mmol) and 4-(methylthio)-2-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-carbonitrile (74 mg, 0.48 mmol) in n-BuOH (5 mL) was heated to 160° C. in a microwave reactor for 1 h. The reaction was repeated with 200 mg (0.26 mmol) of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate as above and the combined crude material was first purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane and then by C8 reverse phase chromatography (acetonitrile-water, 0.1% TFA) to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-cyano-5-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate trifluoroacetate salt (155 mg, 24%) as a brown oil. m/z (MH+) 858.7 for C52H95N3O6.TFA. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.83-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-2.8 (m, 64H); 2.26-2.3 (m, 6H); 2.9-3.1 (m, 4H); 3.21-3.32 (m, 2H); 3.74-3.76 (m, 2H); 4.79-4.85 (m, 4H); 9.13-9.21 (m, 1H); 11.5 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: BW. Compound 82. Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((5-amino-1,3,4-thiadiazol-2-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate Trifluoroacetate Salt

description.p: To a mixture of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-(methylamino)-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl) amino)octanoate (250 mg, 0.28 mmol)) in CH2Cl2 (30 mL) was added PPh3 (223 mg, 0.85 mmol) followed by CCl4 (0.27 mL, 2.84 mmol) at 0° C. The resulting mixture was stirred at room temperature for 4 h. After completion of the reaction (confirmed by TLC and MS), the solvents were removed in a rotary evaporator and the residue purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol to dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-(methylamino)-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (165 mg, 58%) as a pale yellow oil. m/z (MH+) 864.7 for C50H97N5O4S. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.81-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.69 (m, 64H); 2.05-2.29 (m, 6H); 2.8-3.19 (m, 9H); 3.49-3.54 (m, 2H); 4.80-4.87 (m, 2H); 6.23 (br s, 1H); 6.9 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: BY. Compound 85. Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-(dimethylamino)-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate
Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-methoxy-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate
description.p: To a mixture of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (123 mg, 0.75 mmol)) in methanol (3 mL) was added 3,4-dimethoxy-1,2,5-thiadiazole 1-oxide (285 mg, 0.37 mmol). The resultant mixture was stirred at room temperature for 1 h. After completion of the reaction solvents were removed in a rotary evaporator and the residue purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-methoxy-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (3, 192 mg, 29%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.83-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.82 (m, 66H); 2.2-2.65 (m, 10H); 3.54-3.58 (m, 2H); 4.09 (s, 3H); 4.80-4.87 (m, 2H); 9.3 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-(dimethylamino)-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate
description.p: To a mixture of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-methoxy-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (186 mg, 0.21 mmol)) in methanol (3 mL) was added dimethylamine (1.06 mL, 2.1 mmol, 2M in MeOH). The resulting mixture was stirred at room temperature overnight. After completion of the reaction (confirmed by TLC and MS), the solvents were removed in a rotary evaporator and the residue purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((4-(dimethylamino)-1-oxido-1,2,5-thiadiazol-3-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (130 mg, 69%) as a light yellow oil. m/z (MH+) 894.6 for C51H99N5O5S. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.81-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.75 (m, 66H); 2.25-2.69 (m, 10H); 3.22 (s, 6H); 3.59-3.62 (m, 2H); 4.80-4.85 (m, 2H); 8.4 (br s, 1H).

description.p: A mixture of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (100 mg, 0.13 mmol) and trimethyl orthoformate (2 mL) in n-BuOH (5 mL) was refluxed for 1 h. After completion of the reaction the excess solvents were evaporated. The residue was dissolved in MeOH (10 mL), methanesulfonamide (15 mg, 0.16 mmol) added and the resultant mixture was heated to 100° C. for 1 h. The mixture was allowed to cool to room temperature and conc. The reaction was repeated with 200 mg (0.26 mmol) of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate as above and the combined crude material was purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl (E)-8-((3-(N-(methylsulfonyl)formimidamido)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (130 mg, 38%) as a light yellow oil. m/z (MH+) 856.7 for C49H97N3O6S. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.83-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.8 (m, 66H); 2.2-2.7 (m, 10H); 2.9 (s, 3H); 3.48-3.51 (m, 2H); 4.80-4.87 (m, 2H); 8.1 (br m, 1H); 9.15 (br s, 1H).

The resultant mixture was stirred at room temperature for 1 h. After complete conversion had occurred methylhydrazine (21 μL, 0.4 mmol) was added to the above mixture. The resultant mixture was refluxed for 18 h. The excess solvent was evaporated and purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((3-amino-1-methyl-1H-1,2,4-triazol-5-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (120 mg, 35%) as a light brown oil. m/z (MH+) 847.7 for C50H98N6O4. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.83-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.8 (m, 66H); 2.2-2.6 (m, 10H); 3.3 (s, 3H); 3.38-3.48 (m, 2H); 3.81 (br s, 2H), 4.80-4.87 (m, 2H); 6.31-6.35 (br m, 1H).
description.heading: CB. Compound 88. Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((3-nitro-1H-pyrrol-2-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate
(Z)—N-(2,2-Diethoxyethyl)-1-(methylthio)-2-nitroethen-1-amine
description.p: A mixture of glycinaldehyde diethylacetal (2.0 g, 15 mmol)) and 1,1-bis(methylthio)-2-nitroethene (2.5 g, 15 mmol) in ethanol (25 mL) was refluxed for 20 h. After completion of the reaction, the solvents were removed by rotary evaporator. The crude product was purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-5% acetone in dichloromethane to give (Z)—N-(2,2-diethoxyethyl)-1-(methylthio)-2-nitroethen-1-amine (2.2 g, 60%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 1.22-1.26 (m, 6H); 2.43 (s, 3H); 3.51-3.58 (m, 4H); 3.71-3.81 (m, 2H); 4.613-4.66 (m, 1H); 6.56 (s, 1H); 10.45 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: 2-(Methylthio)-3-nitro-1H-pyrrole
description.p: Dry HCl gas was passed through a mixture of (Z)—N-(2,2-diethoxyethyl)-1-(methylthio)-2-nitroethen-1-amine (1.25 g, 5 mmol)) in ether (100 mL) at 5-10° C. for 3 h. After completion of the reaction, the mixture was quenched with 10% K2CO3 solution. The organic layer was dried over anhydrous Na2SO4, filtered and evaporated to give 2-(methylthio)-3-nitro-1H-pyrrole (730 mg, 92%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, DMSO-d6): δ 2.57 (s, 3H); 6.71 (m, 1H); 6.92 (m, 1H); 10.82 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: 2-(Methylsulfinyl)-3-nitro-1H-pyrrole
description.p: To a mixture of 2-(methylthio)-3-nitro-1H-pyrrole (100 mg, 0.63 mmol)) in CH2Cl2:MeOH (3:1, 9 mL) was added mCPBA (141 mg, 0.63 mmol, 77% approx) at 0° C. The resultant mixture was stirred for 30 min (monitored by TLC). After completion of the reaction, the mixture was diluted with CH2Cl2 (10 mL), washed with saturated NaHCO3, dried over anhydrous Na2SO4, filtered and evaporated to give 2-(methylsulfinyl)-3-nitro-1H-pyrrole (60 mg, 54%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, DMSO-d6): δ 2.95 (s, 3H); 6.82 (m, 1H); 7.1 (m, 1H); 11.2 (br s, 1H).
description.heading: Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((3-nitro-1H-pyrrol-2-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate

The excess solvents were removed in rotary evaporator and the residue purified by silica gel chromatography with 0-10% methanol in dichloromethane to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((3-nitro-1H-pyrrol-2-yl)amino)propyl)(8-oxo-8-(undecan-3-yloxy)octyl)amino)octanoate (120 mg, 21%) as a light brown oil. m/z (MH+) 861.7 for C51H96N4O6. 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3): δ 0.83-0.89 (m, 12H); 1.15-1.69 (m, 65H); 1.8-1.95 (m, 2H); 2.19-2.32 (m, 4H); 2.5-2.75 (m, 6H); 3.35-3.63 (m, 2H); 4.80-4.87 (m, 2H); 6.09-6.12 (m, 1H); 6.39-6.42 (m, 1H); 7.61-7.7 (m, 1H).
description.heading: CC. Compound 89: Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-(ethylsulfonamido)propyl)(8-((2-methylnonyl)oxy)-8-oxooctyl)amino)octanoate
2-Methylnonyl 8-bromooctanoate

The reaction was allowed to stir at rt for 16 h. The reaction was diluted with DCM and washed with sat. NaHCO3, followed by brine. The organic layer was separated, dried over Na2SO4, filtered, and evaporated under vacuum. The residue was purified by silica gel chromatography with (0-20%) EtOAc in hexanes to obtain 2-methylnonyl 8-bromooctanoate (5.1 g, 14.04 mmol, 82%). 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3) δ: ppm 3.98 (m, 2H); 3.43 (t, 2H); 2.33 (t, 2H); 1.93-1.74 (m, 3H); 1.72-1.09 (m, 20H); 0.93 (m, 6H).
description.heading: Heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)propyl)amino)octanoate
description.p: A solution of heptadecan-9-yl 8-bromooctanoate 4 (69.2 g, 0.15 mole) and tert-butyl (3-aminopropyl)carbamate (130.6 g, 0.75 mole) in 500 mL ethanol was heated to 65° C. overnight. The reaction mixture was concentrated, and the crude was purified by flash column chromatography (SiO2: methanol/dichloromethane 0-20%) to get heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)propyl)amino)octanoate (62 g, 74%) as light yellow oil. This was heated to 80° C. and stirred for 14 hours. The mixture was allowed to cool to room temp., filtered through Celite, the filter solids washed with propionitrile and the filtrate conc. The residue was dissolved in heptane, washed twice with acetonitrile and conc. to a slightly yellow oil. This residue was purified by silica gel chromatography (0-20% ethyl acetate in hexanes) to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)propyl)(8-((2-methylnonyl)oxy)-8-oxooctyl)amino)octanoate (6.12 g, 7.3 mmol, 82%) as a slightly yellow oil. The reaction was allowed to cool to room temp., diluted with ca. 5 mL of an aqueous 10% sodium carbonate solution and extracted three times with EtOAc. The organics were combined, dried (Na2SO4), filtered and the filtrate conc. to a yellow oil. This was dissolved in heptane, washed twice with acetonitrile, then conc. and dried under vacuum to give heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-((2-methylnonyl)oxy)-8-oxooctyl)amino)octanoate (570 mg, 0.77 mmol, 85%) as a colorless oil. description.p: To a solution of heptadecan-9-yl 8-((3-aminopropyl)(8-((2-methylnonyl)oxy)-8-oxooctyl)amino)octanoate (200 mg, 0.271 mmol) and triethylamine (200 μL, 1.43 mmol) in DCM (6.782 mL) at 0° C. was added cyclopropanesulfonyl chloride (59.114 mg, 0.326 mmol) in DCM (1 mL). description.heading: Example 2: Sample Formulations
description.p: Nanoparticle compositions including a therapeutic and/or prophylactic can be optimized according to the selection of a compound according to Formula (I), (I-1), (A), (A-1), (A-1a), or (A-1b), the selection of additional lipids, the amount of each lipid in the lipid component, and the wt:wt ratio of the lipid component to the therapeutic and/or prophylactic. Nanoparticle compositions including DSPC as a phospholipid, cholesterol as a structural lipid, PEG 2 as a PEG lipid, and a compound according to Formula (I), (I-1), (A), (A-1), (A-1a), or (A-1b) were prepared. The ratios of the lipids were 50:10:38:2 mol % for the lipid according to Formula (I), (I-1), (A), (A-1), (A-1a), or (A-1b):DSPC:cholesterol:PEG 2. Tables 2a, 2b, and 3-5 summarize the characteristics of the formulations.

As shown in Tables 2a and 2b, the choice of compound according to Formula (I), (I-1), (A), (A-1), (A-1a), or (A-1b) affects the size (e.g., diameter), polydispersity index (“PDI”), and encapsulation efficiency (“% EE”) of the compositions. Table 3 shows the pKa of nanoparticles comprising compounds of the disclosure. Table 4 summarizes the surface hydrophobicity of nanoparticles comprising compounds of the disclosure as determined by Generalized Polarization by Laurdan (GPL). Laurdan, a fluorescent aminonaphthalene ketone lipid, was post-inserted into the nanoparticle surface and the fluorescence spectrum of Laurdan was collected to determine the normalized Generalized Polarization (N-GP). Higher N-GP indicates a less polar surface. Table 5 shows heparin-sepharose binding of nanoparticles comprising compounds of the disclosure.

description.heading: Example 3: Expression of hEPO and ApoE Binding Induced by Sample Formulations
description.p: The expression of hEPO mRNA in CD1-mice was measured 6 h after intravenous administration of nanoparticles comprising a compound of the disclosure, DSPC, cholesterol, and PEG 2 in a ratio of 50:10:38:2. The nanoparticles had a molar ratio of lipid nitrogen to RNA phosphate (N:P) of 3.4. Each composition was dosed to 8 animals at an mRNA dose of 0.5 mg/kg. The hEPO expression of nanoparticles of the disclosure is summarized in Table 6.

The ApoE binding affinity, i.e., the affinity of binding between nanoparticles comprising compounds of the disclosure and the serum protein ApoE, was determined by binding the nanoparticles to beads, then incubating them with known quantities of immunoglobulin (IgM). The quantity of protein bound to the nanoparticle was then determined by flow cytometry. The ApoE binding affinity of nanoparticles of the disclosure is summarized in Table 7.

description.heading: Example 4: mRNA Integrity Induced by Sample Formulations
description.p: Integrity of mRNA comprised in nanoparticles of the disclosure, i.e., the percentages of intact mRNA, mRNA adducts, and mRNA hydrolysis products, after 2 weeks of storage at 25° C. was determined by RP-IP (Reverse-Phase Ion-Pairing HPLC) using UV detection at 260 nm. Total purity and impurities are calculated as percent peak area.
